  "prompt": "Is every fossil a missing link?",
  "response": "No, not every fossil is considered a \"missing link.\" The term \"missing link\" is often used informally to describe a transitional fossil that fills a gap in the evolutionary lineage between two species or groups of organisms. These fossils provide evidence of how one species may have evolved into another over time.\n\nHowever, most fossils represent organisms that are not necessarily transitional forms but are instead examples of species that existed at a particular point in time. While these fossils are valuable for understanding the diversity and history of life on Earth, they do not always serve as direct evidence of evolutionary transitions.\n\nIn summary:\n- **Transitional fossils** (sometimes called \"missing links\") are fossils that show intermediate characteristics between ancestral and descendant species.\n- **Non-transitional fossils** represent species that are not directly part of a lineage leading to another species but still contribute to our understanding of biodiversity and evolution.\n\nThe concept of a \"missing link\" can also be misleading, as evolution is a continuous process with many branches, and no single fossil can fully represent the complexity of evolutionary change.",
